0-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/nc190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|editor-last=Forstall|editor-first=Richard L.|date=March 27, 1995|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|date=April 2, 2001|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=September 11, 2013 }}</ref> of 2000, there were 10,677 people, 4,593 households, and 3,169 families residing in the county.  The [[population density]] was 46 people per square mile (18/km\u00b2).  There were 6,412 housing units at an average density of 27 per square&nbsp;mile (11/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the county was 95.69% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 1.23% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.26% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.20% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.01% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.75% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.86% from two or more races.  4.96% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 4,593 households out of which 24.80% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.30% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.50% had a female householder with no husband present, and 31.00% were non-families. 27.80% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.00% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.28 and the average family size was 2.75.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 19.40% under the age of 18, 7.40% from 18 to 24, 26.30% from 25 to 44, 27.70% from 45 to 64, and 19.20% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females there were 97.10 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 95.50 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $29,244, and the median income for a family was $38,473. Males had a median income of $25,462 versus $18,851 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $17,691.  About 11.30% of families and 17.20% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.80% of those under age 18 and 25.00% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Map of Alleghany County North Carolina With Municipal and Township Labels.PNG|thumb|300px|Map of Alleghany County, North Carolina With Municipal and Township Labels]]\n\n===Town===\n* [[Sparta, North Carolina|Sparta]] (county seat)\n\n===Townships===\n*[[Cherry Lane Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Cherry Lane]]\n*[[Cranberry Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Cranberry]]\n*[[Gap Civil Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Gap Civil]]\n*[[Glade Creek Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Glade Creek]]\n*[[Piney Creek Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Piney Creek]]\n*[[Prathers Creek Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Prathers Creek]]\n*[[Whitehead Township, Alleghany County, North Carolina|Whitehead]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n* [[Cherry Lane, North Carolina|Cherry Lane]]\n* [[Ennice, North Carolina|Ennice]]\n* [[Glade Valley, North Carolina|Glade Valley]]\n* [[Laurel Springs, North Carolina|Laurel Springs]]\n* [[Piney Creek, North Carolina|Piney Creek]]\n* [[Roaring Gap, North Carolina|Roaring Gap]]\n* [[Scottville, North Carolina|Scottville]]\n* [[Twin Oaks, North Carolina|Twin Oaks]]\n\n===Population ranking===\n\nThe population ranking of the following table is based on the [[2010 United States census|2010 census]] of Alleghany County.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/2010census/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061210235906/http://www.census.gov/2010census/ |archivedate=2006-12-10 }}</ref>\n\n'''\u2020''' ''county seat''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!City/Town/etc.\n!Municipal type\n!Population (2010 Census)\n'''\n|- style=\"background-color:#F0F8FF;\"\n| ''only incorporated community''\n|'''\u2020''' '''[[Sparta, North Carolina|Sparta]]''' \n| Town\n| 1,770\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Robert L. Doughton]] (1863\u20131954), [[United States Congressman]] from Alleghany County from 1911\u20131953. From 1933\u20131947 he was the Chairman of the [[House Ways and Means Committee]]. He used his influence as Chairman to create the [[Blue Ridge Parkway]], which runs along the county's eastern and southern borders. Doughton Park, the largest and most popular park on the Parkway, is named in his honor. He also played a major role in the passage of the [[Social Security Act]].\n*[[Rufus A. Doughton]] (1857\u20131946), older brother of Robert Doughton. He served as the [[Speaker of the North Carolina House of Representatives]], and was [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]] from 1893-1897.\n*[[Del Reeves]] (1932\u20132007), country music entertainer on the United Artists record label.  He became a member of the Grand Ole Opry in 1966 and his record \"Girl on the Billboard\" sold over a million copies.\n*[[Zach Galifianakis]] (born 1969), stand-up comedian and actor, lives on a farm near Sparta and splits his time between the farm and his work in New York City.\n*[[Bertie Dickens]] (1902-1994), old-time banjo player who lived most of her life in [[Ennice, North Carolina]]. She received the [[North Carolina Heritage Award]] in 1992.\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in North Carolina#Alleghany County|National Register of Historic Places listings in Alleghany County, North Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*[http://alleghanynews.com/ Alleghany News]\n\n{{coord|36.49|-81.13|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-NC_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Alleghany County, North Carolina\n| North     = [[Grayson County, Virginia]]\n| Northeast =\n| East      = [[Surry County, North Carolina|Surry County]]\n| Southeast =\n| South     = [[Wilkes County, North Carolina|Wilkes County]]\n| Southwest =\n| West      = [[Ashe County, North Carolina|Ashe County]]\n| Northwest =\n}}\n\n{{Alleghany County, North Carolina}}\n{{North_Carolina}}HEALTHCARE RISKS AND BREACH OF FIDUCIARY DUTY REGARDING HEALTHCARE/SOCIAL WORK\n\nAlleghany County was named as a location with risk of death by radon poisoning by the North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services in January of 2020.<sup>[1]</sup>\n\nAlso in 2020, the undereducated public relied heavily upon funding outside the county to naively and ignorantly address an alleged \u2018opioid crisis\u2019, utilizing a three-year grand award of up to $275,000 through AppHealthCare.<sup>[2]</sup>\u00a0 The research that the U.S. Health and Human Services composed in 2019 to indicate the severity of opioid crisis and the need for employment assistance revealed that Alleghany County was in the category of the least need for program engagement.<sup>[3]</sup>\u00a0 \u00a0Potentially undereducated county government officials, unwittingly informed that there was an \u2018opioid crisis\u2019, could have possibly spent time instead serving the public effectively through supporting child abuse education, child abuse awareness, and creating a program in the community to build protective factors against abuse so that fewer children came into care and custody of Alleghany County Department of Social Services and were primarily and permanently institutionalized/group homes rather than given back to their natural parents or achieved rigorously-scrutinized adoptive homes.<sup>[4]</sup>\n\nPOLITICS\n\nRepublican and a practicing attorney in the Alleghany County judicial district, Donna L. Shumate of Sparta, is running for the 2020 District Court judgeship now held by Judge Jeanie Houston of Hamptonville due to the Judge\u2019s relinquishment of position.<sup>[5]</sup>\u00a0 It should be an easy race when the incumbent steps down willingly, so Ms. Shumate might have a better chance at winning the race (unlike when she ran unsuccessfully in 2014 against current Judge Crumpton<sup>[6]</sup>). \u00a0Ms. Shumate has similarly to employing persons to her elusive businesses, knowingly and voluntarily outsourced her campaign advertisement to companies outside of the Alleghany County area.<sup>[7]</sup>\u00a0 When Ms. Shumate couldn\u2019t garner enough support for her campaign from the locals she is supposed to be serving as a potential future judge, she enlisted the help of the county\u2019s Republican Party and financed the majority of her campaign advertising herself.[3]\n----[1] <nowiki>https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2020/01/20/n-c-gives-away-radon-test-kits/</nowiki>\n\n[2] <nowiki>https://www.wataugademocrat.com/news/apphealthcare-continues-fight-against-opioid-abuse-with-new-grant/article_01e48a68-8980-58dd-948a-b9aaa082b4ac.html</nowiki>\n\n[3] \n\n[4] <nowiki>http://fosteringcourtimprovement.org/nc/County/Alleghany/incare_charts.html</nowiki>\n\n[5] <nowiki>https://www.journalpatriot.com/news/file-for-county-commissioner-for-school-board/article_2ee502ba-2366-11ea-ab5f-4bc2856e079d.html</nowi