ords|A&M Octone]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]]\n* Maroon 5 <small>(exec.)</small>\n* [[Benny Blanco]]\n* [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[Call and Response: The Remix Album]]\n| prev_year    = 2008\n| next_title   = [[Overexposed (album)|Overexposed]]\n| next_year    = 2012\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Hands All Over\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\n | single1date = June 22, 2010\n | single2     = [[Give a Little More]]\n | single2date = August 17, 2010\n | single3     = [[Never Gonna Leave This Bed]]\n | single3date = January 24, 2011\n | single4     = [[Moves like Jagger]]\n | single4date = June 21, 2011\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Hands All Over''''' is the third studio album by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Maroon 5]]. Produced by veteran producer [[Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]], the album was released by [[A&M Octone Records]] in September 2010 and debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"billboard 200\"/> The standard edition of the album includes three singles: \"[[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\", \"[[Give a Little More]]\" and \"[[Never Gonna Leave This Bed]]\".\n\nOn July 12, 2011, the band re-released the album to include their summer hit and the fourth single \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\".<ref name=rerelease>{{cite news|title=\"Moves Like Jagger\" Now On Hands All Over|url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/moves_like_jagger_now_on_hands_all_over/|access-date=July 15, 2011|newspaper=Maroon5.com|date=July 12, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104194526/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/moves_like_jagger_now_on_hands_all_over|archive-date=January 4, 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe band began writing the songs from the third album, after winding down from [[It Won't Be Soon Before Long Tour|a world tour]] in support of their second album ''[[It Won't Be Soon Before Long]]''. Several months later, the band received a phone call from [[Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]], who had heard the band were beginning to write a new album, and expressed an interest in producing it.<ref name=\"HAO Info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/maroon_5_announce_2010_north_american_tour_and_new_album_hands_all_over/ |title=News |publisher=Maroon 5 |date=2010-05-10 |access-date=2010-08-06 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517101726/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/maroon_5_announce_2010_north_american_tour_and_new_album_hands_all_over |archive-date=2013-05-17 |df= }}</ref> In a press release on their official website, the album is described as \"a killer hybrid of [[Rock music|rock]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[funk]] and [[R&B]].\"<ref name=\"HAO Info\"/>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', the band revealed they spent two months writing and recording their third album with producer Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange in his recording studio in [[Lake Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]. Lead singer Adam Levine, spoke about the experience of working with Lange: \"He worked me harder than anyone ever has,\" [...] \"I would come in with a finished song, and he'd say, 'That's a good start. Now strip it down to the drums and start over.' The coolest thing about him is that not only has he been a huge, legendary producer, but he also is a legit, serious writer.\"<ref name=\"RS Interview\">{{cite magazine|author= Rolling Stone |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14639/87461 |title=Inside Maroon 5's Sessions for Fall Album 'Hands All Over' &#124; Rolling Stone Music |magazine=Rollingstone.com |date=2010-05-18 |accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref>\n''Rolling Stone'' has said that the resulting disc is the band's brightest-sounding and poppiest yet and that it delivers Lange's mix of catchy hooks and punchy rhythms.<ref name=\"RS Interview\"/> Levine has also said about the album: \"Our first record was a reflection of my love for [[Stevie Wonder]]. With the second I kept going back and forth between [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[The Police]]. But there was no one on my mind for this album. It's just great pop.\"<ref name=\"RS Interview\"/> In a separate interview, however, Levine said that the album was influenced by [[Tupac Shakur]] and [[Marvin Gaye]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Justin|last=Harp|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a283263/adam-levine-reveals-musical-influences.html#~phRXFgwCh1YJLj|title=Adam Levine 'reveals musical influences'|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 20, 2010|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref> The album artwork was revealed on July 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/hands_all_over_album_artwork_revealed/ |title=News |publisher=Maroon 5 |date= |access-date=2010-08-06 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724193742/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/hands_all_over_album_artwork_revealed |archive-date=2010-07-24 |df= }}</ref> The cover photo for the album was taken by 19-year-old photographer Rosie Hardy, who also serves as the model in the photo. Hardy took the photo herself in just under an hour, in her own bedroom from the town of [[Buxton]], United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Rosie Hardy \u2013 Photographer of the HANDS ALL OVER album cover|url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/interview_with_rosie_hardy_photographer_of_the_hands_all_over_album_cover/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102100122/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/interview_with_rosie_hardy_photographer_of_the_hands_all_over_album_cover/|archive-date=2013-11-02|df=}}</ref>\n\nA web series titled ''Palm Trees & Power Lines'', was released in three parts: ''Part 1'' on August 23, ''Part 2'' on October 11, and ''Part 3'' on December 3, 2010, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/palm_trees_power_lines_webisode/|title=Palm Trees & Power Lines Webisode|accessdate=January 25, 2020|date=August 23, 2010|work=Maroon 5.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826042742/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/palm_trees_power_lines_webisode/|archivedate=August 26, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maroon5.com/videos/palm-trees-power-lines-part-2-or-3|title=Palm Trees & Power Lines (Part 2 or 3)|work=Maroon 5.com|date=October 11, 2010|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maroon5.com/videos/palm-trees-power-lines-part-3-or-3|title=Palm Trees & Power Lines (Part 3 or 3)|work=Maroon 5.com|date=December 3, 2010|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref> The series follows the band's journey on [[Palm Trees & Power Lines Tour|their 2010 promo tour]] and performing with songs from the album.\n\n==Singles==\n* The lead single to be taken from the album is \"[[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\". It was released on June 22, 2010. The music video for the single was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1639494/20100518/maroon_5.jhtml |title=Maroon 5 Get Violent In 'Misery' Video \u2013 News Story &#124; Music, Celebrity, Artist News &#124; MTV News |publisher=Mtv.com |date=2010-05-18 |accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref> The song reached #14 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n* The second single is \"[[Give a Little More]]\", and was released on August 17, 2010. The music video was directed by [[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]].<ref name=\"videostatic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.videostatic.com/vs/2010/07/booked-maroon-5-paul-hunter-dir.html |title=Music Video News: BOOKED: Maroon 5 \u2013 Paul Hunter, dir |publisher=Video Static |date=2010-07-28 |accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref>\n* The third official single, \"[[Never Gonna Leave This Bed]]\", was released to Australian radio in January 2011. In late January 2011, the song was listed under Cool New Music on All Access in the Hot Adult Contemporary section and in early February 2011, it started gaining airplay there, even though an official Hot AC radio adds date never came to fruition. It officially impacted [[mainstream]] radio on May 17, 2011.<ref name=\"allaccess\">{{cite web|url =http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title =Top 40/Mainstream \u2013 Future Releases &#124; Mainstream Hit Songs Being Released and Their Release Dates|work =All Access|publisher =|accessdate =2011-05-04}}</ref> The music video for the song was shot on January 12, 2011<ref>[http://popline.mtv.uol.com.br/de-pijama-adam-levine-grava-novo-videoclipe-do-maroon-5-com-nvamoda With pajamas, Adam Levine records new video with his band Maroon 5 with girlfriend] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116040643/http://popline.mtv.uol.com.br/de-pijama-adam-levine-grava-novo-videoclipe-do-maroon-5-com-nvamoda |date=2011-01-16 }} ''Popline'' Retrieved 2011-01-13</ref> and premiered exclusively on ''[[Just Jared]]'' on February 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suuuper-stars.blogspot.com/2011/02/maroon-5-gonna-leave-this-bed-video.html|title=Maroon 5's 'Never Gonna Leave This Bed' Video Premiere \u2013 EXCLUSIVE|work=Super Stars|date=February 4, 2011|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref> The band performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' on January 17.<ref>Maroon 5 Brasil (2011-01-18) (in Portuguese) [http://www.maroon5br.com/2011/01/18/maroon-5-performa-never-gonna-leave-this-bed-no-jay-leno/ Maroon 5 performa \u201cNever Gonna Leave This Bed\u201d no Jay Leno] ''Maroon 5 News'' Retrieved 2011-01-18</ref><ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/cool-new-music Hot modern-AC/ Coll New Music] ''All Access''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac|title=Hot-Modern-Adult Contemporary Popular Songs, Alternative Rock, AC Music, Radio News, - ...|author=|date=|website=allaccess.com|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> The song debuted at #35 on the ''Billboard''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Hot [[Adult Pop Songs]] and reached #55 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|url =http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/473190/chart-highlights-adult-pop-rap-songs-more|title =Chart Highlights: Adult Pop, Rap Songs & More|work =Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate =2011-02-08}}</ref>\n* The fourth official single, \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\", featuring [[Christina Aguilera]], was released on June 21, 2011, being the first single from the re-release of the album. The song debuted at number 8 on the Hot 100, the first Top 10 for Maroon 5 and Aguilera, since \"[[Makes Me Wonder]]\" and \"[[Keeps Gettin' Better]]\" respectively. The song peaked at #1 on the issue of August 31, 2011, making this song the band's second #1 (after \"Makes Me Wonder\" in 2007) and Aguilera's fifth number-one (after \"[[Lady Marmalade]]\" in 2001).<ref name=itunesalbum>{{cite news|title=Moves Like Jagger (The Voice Performance) [feat. Christina Aguilera] \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/moves-like-jagger-the-voice/id443177467|accessdate=July 15, 2011|newspaper=[[iTunes]]|date=June 21, 2011}}</ref> The band performed the song several times, including on ''[[America's Got Talent]]'', ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'', ''[[Today (American TV program)|The Today Show]]'', ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.\n\n===Other songs===\n* A music video for the title track \"[[Hands All Over (Maroon 5 song)|Hands All Over]]\", was released on December 22, 2010. Its music video, which was directed by Don Tyler and features stylized animations of the band members and a flirtatious nude woman.<ref name=\"RTT News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/Content/EntertainmentNews.aspx?Section=2&Id=1514168&SM=1 |title=Maroon 5 Debuts Video For \"Hands All Over\" \u2013 Entertainment News |publisher=RTT News |date=2010-12-24 |accessdate=2010-12-25}}</ref> The song was featured in the television series ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/medium/season-7/6704|title=Medium \u2013 Talk to the Hand|work=[[Tunefind]]|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* A music video for the song \"Runaway\" was released on April 5, 2011 and instead of featuring the five members of the band, this clip focuses on a surfer who enjoys riding the wave and finds solitude in the sea.<ref name=\"RunawayVid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/new_video_for_runaway/|title=Maroon 5 News \u2013 New Video for \"Runaway\"|publisher=Maroon 5.com|date=2011-04-05|access-date=2011-04-05|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410072919/http://www.maroon5.com/news_detail/new_video_for_runaway/|archive-date=2011-04-10|df=}}</ref> \n* A music video for \"Out of Goodbyes\" (with country group [[Lady Antebellum]]) released on May 16, 2011 and was directed by Travis Schneider. The video features singer/actor [[Dwight Yoakam]] and actress [[Diora Baird]]. It shows the woman cleaning a bloody wound and removing a bullet from the man's chest, after which she gets up to leave, but grabs her revolver and shoots him.<ref name=\"OutofGoodbyesVid\">{{cite web|url=http://perezhilton.com/2011-05-16-new-maroon-5-featuring-lady-antebellum|title=New Maroon 5 Featuring Lady Antebellum!|publisher=Maroon 5.com|date=2011-05-16|accessdate=2011-05-17}}</ref> The song did not enter the Hot 100 chart, but it did peak at the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles]] chart at number three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/3123797|title=Bubbling Under Hot 100 \u2013 Issue Date: 2010-10-09|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref> \n* \"Stutter\" charted at #84 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, due to strong digital downloads when the album was released.<ref>[http://www.yoursonglyrics.com/stutter-maroon-5/ Stutter \u2013 Maroon 5 Song] ''Your Song'' Retrieved 2011-01-21</ref><ref>[http://bloglyrics.net/maroon-5-stutter-lyrics-and-music-review.html Maroon 5 \u2013 Stutter (Lyrics and Music Review)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326181328/http://bloglyrics.net/maroon-5-stutter-lyrics-and-music-review.html |date=2011-03-26 }} ''Blog Lyrics'' Retrieved 2011-01-21</ref>\n* The two songs are featured on television shows \"How\" in ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' and \"Don't Know Nothing\" in ''[[Undercovers (TV series)|Undercovers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/medium/season-7/6704|title=One Tree Hill \u2013 We All Fall Down|work=Tunefind|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/undercovers/season-1/6834|title=Undercovers \u2013 Assassin|work=Tunefind|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n<!-- 10 REVIEWS MAX -->\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 5.4/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/2156/Maroon-5-Hands-All-Over.aspx |title=Hands All Over by Maroon 5 reviews |website=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n| MC = 63/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/hands-all-over/maroon-5 |title=Reviews for Hands All Over by Maroon 5 |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2010-09-30}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hands-all-over-mw0002022758 |title=Hands All Over \u2013 Maroon 5 |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = C+<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite journal |last=Greenblatt |first=Leah |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2010/09/22/hands-all-over |title=Hands All Over |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2010-09-22 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[IGN]]''\n| rev3Score = 7/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Carle |first=Chris |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/09/24/maroon-5-hands-all-over-review |title=Maroon 5: Hands All Over Review |work=[[IGN]] |date=2010-09-24 |accessdate=2011-04-25}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Gill |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-maroon-5-hands-all-over-aampm-2081270.html |title=Album: Maroon 5, Hands All Over (A&M) |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2010-09-17 |access-date=2019-04-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919215717/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-maroon-5-hands-all-over-aampm-2081270.html |archive-date=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|2.5|4}}<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Mikael |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/09/album-review-maroon-5s-hands-all-over.html |title=Album review: Maroon 5's 'Hands All Over' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2010-09-22 |accessdate=2010-10-13}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]''\n| rev6Score = 3/5<ref name=\"nowreview\">{{cite news |last=Keller |first=Jason |url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/maroon-5-2010-09-23/ |title=Maroon 5 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=2010-09-23 |accessdate=2010-09-30}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RollingstoneR\">{{cite journal |last=Rosen |first=Jody |authorlink=Jody Rosen |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/hands-all-over-20100920 |title=Hands All Over |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2010-09-20 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web |last=Dorof |first=Jakob |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/maroon-5-hands-all-over |title=Maroon 5: Hands All Over |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=2010-09-20 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroon 5: Hands All Over |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=162 |date=November 2010 |page=94}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Gardner |first=Elysa |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2010-09-21-listen21_ST_N.htm |title=Maroon 5, ''Hands All Over'': The Right Touch |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2010-09-21 |accessdate=2013-11-15}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Hands All Over'' received a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted score]] of 63 out of 100 from review aggregate website [[Metacritic]], indicating \"generally favorable reviews\", based on 10 reviews from [[music journalism|music critics]].<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[AllMusic]] rated the album very highly with 4.5 out of 5 stars, stating that: \"Some of the cuts may not sink their hooks in immediately, but track for track ''Hands All Over'' is [[Maroon 5]]'s best album, capturing their character and craft in a cool, sleek package\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> Bill Lamb from [[About.com]] was also positive, awarding it with 4 stars (out of 5), saying: \"For their third studio album Maroon 5 add a bit more rock and it looks good on them. There is a loosening up in sound here while keeping the infectious hooks that have always been a major part of the group's appeal. Don't go looking for exceptional depth, but in a period in which mainstream pop sounds are ruling the charts again, Maroon 5 provide a good lesson in exactly how to make a solid pop album\".<ref name=\"about\">Lamb, Bill (2010-09-21) [http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Maroon-5-Hands-All-Over.htm \"Maroon 5 \u2013 Hands All Over (Review) \u2013 ''Maroon 5 Add a Little More Rock''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429212433/http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Maroon-5-Hands-All-Over.htm |date=2013-04-29 }}. [[About.com]]. Retrieved 2011-01-21</ref>\n\nThe [[IGN]] review rated ''Hands All Over'' seven-stars out of ten, claiming that the album is \"programmed to hit all the bases: dance-y tracks, pop anthems, quasi-ballads. Almost every song on this record could be a single...Even though it's formulaic and delivers no surprises, fans of Maroon 5 should find exactly what they are looking for from this record.\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Jakob Dorof from ''[[Slant Magazine]]s'' review was mixed saying, \"It adds a few more gems to the band's growing cache of incredible pop singles and overlooked deep cuts, Hands All Over makes some decent contributions to what could wind up being Maroon 5's true redemption: a damn fine greatest hits record.\"<ref name=\"slant\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' review says that: \"''Hands All Over'' reveals less about who frontman [[Adam Levine]] is than did Maroon 5's previous records; too often the songs cleave to opaque generalities\".<ref name=\"latimes\"/> Hugh Montgomery in ''[[The Observer]]'' wrote that 'Jaunty funk-pop and blustery arena balladry remain the order of the day, while Adam Levine's falsetto whine still proffers all the emotional gravitas of a mosquito'.<ref name=\"GuardianR\">{{cite news |last=Montgomery |first=Hugh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/sep/19/maroon-5-hands-all-review |title=Maroon 5: Hands All Over |work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |date=2010-09-19 |accessdate=2010-09-22}}</ref>\n\n[[Jody Rosen]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' claimed, \"at the helm, the dozen songs on ''Hands All Over'' are models of craftsmanship and efficiency ...\"<ref name=\"RollingstoneR\"/> Fraser McAlpine of [[BBC Music]] noticed that \"The rude guitar sleaze of Hands All Over, or the cocky glam-stomp in [[Stutter]]'s verses show a band who are really at their best when they play pop music like the sleazy rockers they clearly are.\"<ref name=\"BBCR\">{{cite web |last=McAlpine |first=Fraser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/xmrj |title=Music \u2013 Review of Maroon 5 \u2013 Hands All Over |publisher=[[BBC Music]] |date=2010-09-20 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref> ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' review felt that \"This is lead singer Adam Levine's show. Thus, the band's success lives and dies with his delivery. That delivery remains technically sound, though as a whole, the band underwhelms here\".<ref name=\"boston\">{{cite news |last=Rodman |first=Sarah |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/cd_reviews/articles/2010/09/20/on_hands_all_over_maroon_5_sounds_glad_to_be_sad/ |title=They sound glad to be sad |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2010-09-19 |accessdate=2010-09-23}}</ref> The ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'' review also felt that \"It's an accomplished record for singer Adam Levine and his faceless group, even if the whole affair sometimes sounds clinical in its approach\".<ref name=\"nowreview\"/> The [[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo! Music UK]] review was mixed, saying that \"It's hard to imagine how Hands All Over could have been any more underwhelming. In truth the only exceptional thing about it is just how average it is\".<ref name=dotmusic>{{cite web |last=Gennoe |first=Dan |url=http://new.uk.music.yahoo.com/blogs/albumreviewsuk/2035/maroon-5hands-all-over/ |title=Maroon 5 \u2013 \u2018Hands All Over\u2019 \u2013 Album Reviews |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo! Music UK]] |date=2010-09-23 |access-date=2013-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927050119/http://new.uk.music.yahoo.com/blogs/albumreviewsuk/2035/maroon-5hands-all-over |archive-date=2010-09-27 |url-status=dead}}</ref>  The ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review concluded that \"Hands, competent and studio-sleek as it is, too often begs for a fresher muse.<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nOn the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], the album debuted at number two, which despite a high placement sold a relatively weak 142,000 copies, compared to their [[It Won't Be Soon Before Long|previous effort]], which debuted at number-one with 429,000 copies.<ref name=\"billboard 200\">[http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i6bea309148ed3a841841e5e9d8144152 Maroon 5 debuts at number 2 on the Billboard 200] ''Billboard''. Retrieved 2010-09-29.</ref> In the second week, it dropped to #9.<ref>[http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/66598/week-ending-oct-3-2010-americas-most-popular-inmate/ Week Ending Oct. 3, 2010: America's Most Popular Inmate] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210230812/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/66598/week-ending-oct-3-2010-americas-most-popular-inmate/ |date=2010-12-10 }} ''[[Yahoo! Music]]'' Retrieved 2011-03-25</ref> In November 2010, the album was certified Gold by RIAA, denoting a sales of at least 500,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Maroon%205&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50 |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Maroon 5 guitarist [[James Valentine (musician)|James Valentine]] expressed some frustration in the lackluster sales of the ''Hands All Over'', saying a new album may be coming sooner than was originally planned. \"Of course we could have liked it to have done better so far,\" Valentine told ''Billboard'', \"It hasn't sold at the pace that our previous records did.\" The lack of response to the latest record has the band thinking about recording another album sooner than they originally planned, but according to Valentine \"that may not be a bad thing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/948757/maroon-5-would-have-liked-more-success-with-hands-all-over|title=Maroon 5 'Would Have Liked' More Success with 'Hands All Over'|work=Billboard|last=Graff|first=Gary|date=December 27, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}</ref> However, on the week of September 24, 2011, the album returned to the top 10 for the first time since its second week on the chart last October, climbing from number 23 to number 7 with 29,000 copies sold. This was spurred on by a four-day $6.99 sale price in the [[iTunes Store]] as well as the success of \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\", and represented the album's best sales frame since its second chart week and highest rank since its debut.<ref>{{cite news|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=George Strait Lands Top Debut on Billboard 200, Beatles' 1' Re-enters Top 5|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467469/george-strait-lands-top-debut-on-billboard-200-beatles-1-re-enters-top-5|accessdate=15 September 2011|newspaper=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=14 September 2011}}</ref> The album was certified platinum in January 9, 2012{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|type=album|title=Hands All Over|artist=Maroon 5}} and as of April 2012 it has sold 1,079,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grein |first=Paul |url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-april-29-2012-albums-white-good-125919032.html |title=Week Ending April 29, 2012. Albums: White\u2019s In Good Company &#124; Chart Watch (NEW) \u2013 Yahoo! Music |publisher=Music.yahoo.com |date=2012-05-02 |accessdate=2013-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 40:27\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = [[Misery (Maroon 5 song)|Misery]]\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n* [[Adam Levine]]\n* [[Jesse Carmichael]]\n* [[Sam Farrar]]\n}}\n| extra1 = [[Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]]\n| length1 = 3:36\n\n| title2 = [[Give a Little More]]\n| writer2 = {{flat list|\n* Levine\n* Carmichael\n* [[James Valentine (musician)|James Valentine]]\n}}\n| extra2 = Lange\n| length2 = 3:00\n\n| title3 = Stutter\n| writer3 = {{flat list|\n* Levine\n* Farrar\n* [[Matt Flynn (musician)|Matt Flynn]]\n}}\n| extra3 = Lange\n| length3 = 3:16\n\n| title4 = Don't Know Nothing\n| writer4 = {{flat list|\n* Levine\n* Farrar\n}}\n| extra4 = Lange\n| length4 = 3:19\n\n|