{"title_page": "Center for Mexican American Studies at Arlington", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:Center for Mexican American Studies at The University of Texas at Arlington.jpg|thumb|Center for Mexican American Studies at The University of Texas at Arlington]]\n\nThe '''Center for Mexican American Studies''' at [[The University of Texas at Arlington]] is an academic research center that promotes research and the recruitment, retention, and professional development of UTA faculty actively engaged in studies on Latino issues. \n\nThe Center administers an 18-hour academic minor in Mexican American Studies and its annual Distinguished Speaker Series. Additionally, it provides service outreach activities to the Latino community in the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas/Fort Worth Metroplex]] .\n\n== History ==\nThrough the efforts of State Representative [[Roberto Alonzo]] of Dallas, the 73rd [[Texas Legislature]] authorized the creation of CMAS-UTA in 1993. \n\nOn October 12, 1994 the Center held its grand opening under  founding director Dr. Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Guti\u00e9rrez, a member of UTA\u2019s Department of Political Science. Dr. Guti\u00e9rrez\u2019s directorship ended in 1996.\n\nIn 1997, the University named Consulting Director Dr. Neil Foley of the University of Texas, Austin to reconstitute and reactivate the Center, and to search for a new director. Those efforts led to the appointment of Dr. L. Manuel Garc\u00eda y Griego as CMAS director in fall 1999. Dr. Garc\u00eda y Griego relinquished leadership of the Center in 2003.\n\nIn 2003, Interim Director Dr. Alejandro Del Carmen of UTA\u2019s Department of Criminology and Criminal Justice was appointed until 2005. In 2005 Dr. Susan Gonz\u00e1lez Baker became the next CMAS director until 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/mexican-american-studies-director-dies/article_3cfa79cc-24e5-11e5-bd51-3bf82da334d3.html|title=Mexican American studies director dies|first=Kathryn Cargo, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> In 2013, Dr. Christian Zlolniski,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/ebook.php?isbn=9780520939172|title=Janitors, Street Vendors, and Activists|publisher=}}</ref> a member of UTA\u2019s Department of Sociology and Anthropology, took the helm as CMAS director with Dr. William Arce from UTA's Department of English joining in as Assistant Director. In 2015, Dr. Ignacio Ruiz-Perez from the Department of Modern Languages is appointed as the new Assistant Director <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uta.edu/news/releases/2016/02/zlolniski-THECB.php|title=CMAS director Zlolniski appointed to key state committee on Mexican-American studies at Texas colleges, universities - UTA News Center|website=www.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== MAS Minor ==\nThe minor in Mexican American Studies is an interdisciplinary program that offers a strong complement  for students majoring in Liberal Arts, Education, Business, [[Social work|Social Work,]] and [[Nursing]]. The MAS minor enables the student to explore the [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]] and [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] experience. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.uta.edu/coursedescriptions/mas/|title=Mexican American Studies (MAS) < University of Texas Arlington|website=catalog.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Distinguished Speaker Series ==\nThe Distinguished Speaker Series is the annual lineup of speakers who are notable figures within the area of Mexican American Studies. Notable guest speakers have included Dr. [[Jorge Casta\u00f1eda Gutman|Jorge Caste\u00f1eda]] the former [[Foreign minister of Mexico|Foreign Minister of Mexico]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/former-foreign-minister-u-s-mexico-are-equal-partners-in/article_8232efbc-5092-5263-8c14-585f1178f39a.html?mode=jqm&login=|title=Former foreign minister: U.S., Mexico are equal partners in immigration reform|first=Alysia R. Brooks, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> [[Maria Hinojosa|Maria Hinojosa,]] NPR Journalist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arlingtonvoice.com/event/2017/04/18/maria-hinojosa-lecture-ut-arlington|title=Maria Hinojosa lecture at UT Arlington|date=18 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Pia Orrenius, Vice President & Senior Economist at the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas]], [[Leo Chavez|Leo Chavez,]] anthropology professor at the [[University of California, Irvine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/speaker-confronts-negative-immigrant-stereotypes/article_bddafa0c-01f4-11e6-a100-439c4c0ccaf9.html|title=Speaker confronts negative immigrant stereotypes|first=Zahraa Ileiwi, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> and Dr. Neil Foley of the University of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uta.edu/news/releases/2012/03/neil-foley-cmas.php|title=Neil Foley Lecture - UTA News Center|website=www.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:University of Texas at Arlington| ]]\n[[Category:Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Education in Arlington, Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:Center for Mexican American Studies at The University of Texas at Arlington.jpg|thumb|Center for Mexican American Studies at The University of Texas at Arlington]]\n\nThe '''Center for Mexican American Studies''' at [[The University of Texas at Arlington]] is an academic research center that promotes research and the recruitment, retention, and professional development of UTA faculty actively engaged in studies on Latino issues. \n\nThe Center administers an 18-hour academic minor in Mexican American Studies and its annual Distinguished Speaker Series. Additionally, it provides service outreach activities to the Latino community in the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas/Fort Worth Metroplex]] .\n\n== History ==\nThrough the efforts of State Representative [[Roberto Alonzo]] of Dallas, the 73rd [[Texas Legislature]] authorized the creation of CMAS-UTA in 1993. \n\nOn October 12, 1994 the Center held its grand opening under  founding director Dr. Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Guti\u00e9rrez, a member of UTA\u2019s Department of Political Science. Dr. Guti\u00e9rrez\u2019s directorship ended in 1996.\n\nIn 1997, the University named Consulting Director Dr. Neil Foley of the University of Texas, Austin to reconstitute and reactivate the Center, and to search for a new director. Those efforts led to the appointment of Dr. L. Manuel Garc\u00eda y Griego as CMAS director in fall 1999. Dr. Garc\u00eda y Griego relinquished leadership of the Center in 2003.\n\nIn 2003, Interim Director Dr. Alejandro Del Carmen of UTA\u2019s Department of Criminology and Criminal Justice was appointed until 2005. In 2005 Dr. Susan Gonz\u00e1lez Baker became the next CMAS director until 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/mexican-american-studies-director-dies/article_3cfa79cc-24e5-11e5-bd51-3bf82da334d3.html|title=Mexican American studies director dies|first=Kathryn Cargo, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> In 2013, Dr. Christian Zlolniski,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/ebook.php?isbn=9780520939172|title=Janitors, Street Vendors, and Activists|publisher=}}</ref> a member of UTA\u2019s Department of Sociology and Anthropology, took the helm as CMAS director with Dr. William Arce from UTA's Department of English joining in as Assistant Director. In 2015, Dr. Ignacio Ruiz-Perez from the Department of Modern Languages is appointed as the new Assistant Director <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uta.edu/news/releases/2016/02/zlolniski-THECB.php|title=CMAS director Zlolniski appointed to key state committee on Mexican-American studies at Texas colleges, universities - UTA News Center|website=www.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== MAS Minor ==\nThe minor in Mexican American Studies is an interdisciplinary program that offers a strong complement  for students majoring in Liberal Arts, Education, Business, [[Social work|Social Work,]] and [[Nursing]]. The MAS minor enables the student to explore the [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]] and [[Latino]] experience. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.uta.edu/coursedescriptions/mas/|title=Mexican American Studies (MAS) < University of Texas Arlington|website=catalog.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Distinguished Speaker Series ==\nThe Distinguished Speaker Series is the annual lineup of speakers who are notable figures within the area of Mexican American Studies. Notable guest speakers have included Dr. [[Jorge Casta\u00f1eda Gutman|Jorge Caste\u00f1eda]] the former [[Foreign minister of Mexico|Foreign Minister of Mexico]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/former-foreign-minister-u-s-mexico-are-equal-partners-in/article_8232efbc-5092-5263-8c14-585f1178f39a.html?mode=jqm&login=|title=Former foreign minister: U.S., Mexico are equal partners in immigration reform|first=Alysia R. Brooks, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> [[Maria Hinojosa|Maria Hinojosa,]] NPR Journalist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arlingtonvoice.com/event/2017/04/18/maria-hinojosa-lecture-ut-arlington|title=Maria Hinojosa lecture at UT Arlington|date=18 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Pia Orrenius, Vice President & Senior Economist at the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas]], [[Leo Chavez|Leo Chavez,]] anthropology professor at the [[University of California, Irvine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshorthorn.com/news/speaker-confronts-negative-immigrant-stereotypes/article_bddafa0c-01f4-11e6-a100-439c4c0ccaf9.html|title=Speaker confronts negative immigrant stereotypes|first=Zahraa Ileiwi, The Shorthorn|last=staff|publisher=}}</ref> and Dr. Neil Foley of the University of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uta.edu/news/releases/2012/03/neil-foley-cmas.php|title=Neil Foley Lecture - UTA News Center|website=www.uta.edu}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:University of Texas at Arlington| ]]\n[[Category:Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Education in Arlington, Texas]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_for_Mexican_American_Studies_at_Arlington"}
